      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
        <tr> 
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A View of the Core Part 2<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.75)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10381'>Roger "Darkphoenix" Ballou Jr.</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10381&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">  	This continues my exploration into the different Core cards available and in this article I will take a look at what the Core had available in the set Dream&#39;s End.<br>
<br>
I will start by saying that the 5 Shadow Geysers all share this text:   The cost of this geyser is zero if played by a shadow magi of the corresponding region.   You may not play two of the same shadow geyser at the same time.  If your magi leaves play, you may keep all of your geysers except one from being discarded.  Agram discards no geysers when he leaves play.<br>
<br>
Arderial Shadow Geyser            Core Spell           Energy Cost:  5<br>
<br>
	You must discard three Core spells to play this geyser.  Arderial spells cost an additional two energy to play. Your Core spells cost one less energy to play to a minimum of one.<br>
<br>
	I will start by saying that none of the geysers are particularly good in my opinion, the only real value in them is if you are going to try and win the game by dropping all five.  Their effects are too narrow to really be effective against a majority of decks.  This particular geyser is not one of the better ones.  The cost to get it into play is too great for such a piddley effect.<br>
<br>
Grade:  D-<br>
<br>
Cald Shadow Geyser                  Core Spell            Energy Cost:  5<br>
<br>
	To play this geyser you must discard energy from all of your creatures in play equal to the energy cost of their most expensive power.  If you discarded at least five energy play this card.  All powers on Cald cards cost an additional two energy to use.  All powers on your Core cards cost one less energy to a minimum of one.<br>
<br>
	Again too narrow of an effect for such a cost.<br>
<br>
Grade:  D-<br>
<br>
Naroom Shadow Geyser             Core Spell             Energy Cost:  5<br>
<br>
	Discard three of your Core creatures from play to play this card.  Naroom creatures lose two energy when played.  Your Core creatures gain one additional energy when played.<br>
<br>
	This geyser is actually more useful than the rest of the geysers.  I can almost see some people using this in multiplayer.<br>
<br>
Grade:  D+<br>
<br>
Orothe Shadow Geyser               Core Spell             Energy Cost:  5<br>
<br>
	You must discard three of your Core relics from play to play this geyser.  Opponents must pay two additional energy to use powers on Orothe and Universal relics.  Whenever youplay a Core relic each of your opponents must discard a card from their hands.<br>
<br>
	This geyser is almost as useful as the Naroom one.  A few people may play it.<br>
<br>
Grade:  D+<br>
<br>
Underneath Shadow Geyser          Core Spell           Energy Cost:  5<br>
<br>
	You must discard six Core cards from your hand to place this geyser on the table.  All non-Core magi with an Underneath card in play draw one less card during their draw phase.  You must draw one additional card during your draw phase.<br>
<br>
	Ouch!  The cost on this one is truly harsh.  The effect is nice but still nowhere near the cost of this one.<br>
<br>
Grade:  D-<br>
<br>
Stealth                                             Core Spell              Energy Cost:  3<br>
<br>
	Choose any creature in play.  When this creature attacks this turn it removes energy immediately, before energy in normally removed.<br>
	Weave magi may play Stealth.<br>
<br>
	This spell is mediocre.  The cost isn&#39;t that bad, but to get the most use out of it you should play it on a three energy or greater creature attacking a lesser foe.<br>
<br>
Grade:  C-<br>
<br>
Vaporize                                         Core Spell                Energy Cost:  3<br>
<br>
	Choose any one magi in play.  Discard one energy from the chosen magi for every relic the magi has in play.  Discard all that magi&#39;s relics from play.<br>
<br>
	This is one sweet Core spell!  Every deck should have some form of relic removal and this spell is a good one to accomplish that task.  The energy discard on the magi is just a bonus.<br>
<br>
Grade:  A-<br>
<br>
Agram&#39;s Plaything                          Core Relic                Energy Cost:  0<br>
<br>
	Power Puppet Strings:  Until the end of your turn, Agram&#39;s Plaything changes into a creature.  Add one energy to Agram&#39;s Plaything whenever it becomes a creature.  If your magi is Agram add an additional two energy to it.  When Agram&#39;s Plaything becomes a relic remove all energy from it.  <br>
	Starting:  Agram<br>
<br>
	This relic is okay, it basically gives you a free one energy creature (three iram).  Makes Agram a little more useful as a magi.<br>
<br>
Grade:  C-<br>
<br>
Agram&#39;s Staff                                Core Relic                  Energy Cost:  2<br>
<br>
	Effect Mastery:  Your Shadow Magi may play cards from their original region ignoring regional restrictions and penalties.<br>
	Effect Control:  If your magi is Agram, you may play cards that say they may be played by shadow magi.  Agram does not pay a penalty for playing non-Core cards.<br>
<br>
	This relic has slightly below average power.  I could see it being used in some decks that like to use some cards from out of region.<br>
<br>
Grade:  C-<br>
<br>
Secrets of the Book                         Core Relic                  Energy Cost:  0<br>
<br>
	Power Secrets:  Discard three energy from your magi.  Choose any one opposing player and look at their hand.  Draw one card for each creature revealed, and draw two cards for each Naroom non-creature card revealed.  You may only draw up to a maximum of four cards in this manner.<br>
<br>
	This is one very powerful relic!  Not only do you get to look at your opponent&#39;s hand to plan a strategy against them but you get to draw cards!  Sweet!!<br>
<br>
Grade:  A<br>
<br>
Chur                                                 Kybar&#39;s Teeth Shadow Magi<br>
Starting Energy:  15<br>
Energize Rate:  6<br>
Starting Cards:  Borgor, Gorath, Feet of Stone, and Vaporize.<br>
<br>
	Effect Smash:  Whenever a player plays a relic discard that relic from play.<br>
<br>
	Chur in my opinion is a pretty good magi.  Probably best used as a second magi though, so that if he is defeated your next magi may play all the relics you saved up.  Average starting energy and an above average energize rate, coupled with drawing a Vaporize as a starting card make him a decent magi.<br>
<br>
Grade:  B+<br>
<br>
Evil Evu                                            Naroom Shadow Magi                            Alternate Evu<br>
Starting Energy:  15<br>
Energize Rate:  5<br>
Starting Cards:  Furok, Plith, and Dream Rift.<br>
<br>
	You may play Naroom cards ignoring regional restrictions and penalties.  <br>
	Effect Devour:  Whenever an opposing creature is removed from play or reduced to zero energy from one of your cards, draw a card.<br>
<br>
	Evil Evu is another pretty good magi for the Core.  Average Energy and energize rate, decent starting cards and a really good ability.  The only downside to Evil Evu is that he makes a really good magi for a Naroom deck also.<br>
<br>
Grade:  B+<br>
<br>
Hrada                                                  Naroom Shadow Magi<br>
Starting Energy:  16<br>
Energize Rate:  6<br>
Starting Cards:  Garadan, Orok and Shadow Rain.<br>
<br>
	Power Tainted Touch:  Discard two energy from your magi.  Choose any non-Core magi in play.  Until the start of your next turn the chosen magi is a shadow magi of it&#39;s original region.  That magi may still play cards from their original region with a penalty of one energy.  Naroom magi have a regional penalty of two energy instead of one.<br>
<br>
	Hrada is a pretty decent magi to play with, one could definitely do worse.  Above average starting energy and energize rate and two of his starting cards are okay.  The ability on Hrada is okay, it prevents opposing magi from using out of region cards and slows them down when using in region cards.<br>
<br>
Grade:  B<br>
<br>
Ashio                                                    Weave Shadow Magi<br>
Starting Energy:  13<br>
Energize Rate:  6<br>
Starting Cards:  Drush, Flugg, and Binding.<br>
<br>
	Effect Weave Twist:  All cards that specifically reference Core instead reference their own region.  If a card is of multiple regions you choose which region to reference.<br>
<br>
	Ashio is a slightly below average magi.  Below average starting energy, and above average energize rate with only one good starting card.  The effect is too narrow to be generally useful.  This magi will most likely only see an abundance of play in regions where people are scared of Core and play with some of the many Core hosing cards.  The look on those players who do use those cards however, would be priceless when they see this magi going against them.<br>
<br>
Grade:  C-<br>
<br>
Chaos Plith                                            Core Creature                 Alternate Plith<br>
Starting Energy:  5<br>
<br>
	Effect Guile:  Whenever Chaos Plith defeats a creature in an attack draw a card.  If Evu is your magi draw an additional card.<br>
	Naroom magi may play Chaos Plith.<br>
<br>
	This creature is really nice and can be a card drawing monster if you have Evu as one of your magi.  A better than average Core creature.<br>
<br>
Grade:  B<br>
<br>
Dark Furok                                              Core Creature                 Alternate Furok<br>
Starting Energy:  6<br>
<br>
	Effect Revile:  Whenever Dark Furok attacks and loses energy, discard half that amount of energy rounded down to any one creature in play.<br>
	Naroom magi may play Dark Furok.<br>
<br>
	This creature is also really nice and can take out a six energy creature in an attack and then take out another opposing three energy creature with it&#39;s effect.  Nice!!<br>
<br>
Grade:  B+<br>
<br>
Drush                                                        Core Creature  <br>
Starting Energy:  4<br>
<br>
	Effect Vengeance:  If Drush is attacked and defeated, choose any one of the attacking  players creatures in play and discard the creature chosen.<br>
	Weave magi may play Drush.<br>
<br>
	This is another really strong Core creature released in this set.  The ability is really nice, Drush becomes the roadblock nobody wishes to attack and defeat.<br>
<br>
Grade:  A<br>
<br>
Garadan                                                     Core Creature<br>
Starting Energy:  7<br>
<br>
	Effect Spawn:  Whenever Garadan attacks a magi, after energy is removed, you may immediately play any one Core or Naroom creature from your hand with one energy instead of it&#39;s starting energy and without paying any costs.<br>
	Naroom magi may play Garadan.<br>
<br>
	This creature doesn&#39;t impress me.  It is expensive and does not do much for what it costs.  I think that there are definitely better Core creatures around to use.<br>
<br>
Grade:  D<br>
<br>
Harban                                                        Core Creature<br>
Starting Energy:  5<br>
<br>
	Power Browbeat:  Choose any one opposing creature in play with only one energy.  Gain control of the opposing creature.<br>
	Arderial magi may play Harban.<br>
<br>
	This is another pretty good Core creature from this set and puts the cap on a set in which Core received some really nice cards.  Can be extremely useful for getting around some really pesky creatures (ex:  Bwill, Phrup).  Definitely above average.<br>
<br>
Grade:  B-<br>
<br>
<br>
	This article will conclude in my last installment which will take a look at the most recent set, Nightmare&#39;s Dawn.  Until then…….<br>
<br>
--Darkphoenix<br>
